df1 = df.groupby('Year').count() # I create a variable df1 to count the number of games for a given year.
df1 = df1.sort_values('Rank', ascending = 0).head(10) # I order the variable in descending order of the number of occurrences.
df1 = df1.reset_index() # Restores the index to organize the bar chart.

sns.barplot(data = df1, x = 'Year', y = 'Rank', order = df1.Year)
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('TOP 10 number of created games per year')

# I am creating a function that will visualize the number of copies sold for a given category of a variable.
def graph1 (market):
    df2 = df.groupby('Year').sum()
    df2 = df2.sort_values(market , ascending = 0).head(10)
    df2 = df2.reset_index()
    sns.barplot(data = df2, x = 'Year', y = market, order = df2.Year)
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel(market)
    plt.title('TOP 10 number of sold games in milions per year')

Conclusions: The boom of the video game market occurred between 2006 and 2013 is the period with the highest number of years with the number of games produced and the number of copies sold. When it comes to game genres, the Japanese market stands out from other markets. The Japanese prefer to play RPG games, while the 'rest of the world' values action games the most. As a result, the most popular game sold in Japan is different from global trends; in other markets, Wii Sports led the way (except in 'other' markets, where the largest number of copies sold was recorded by GTA:SA), while in the cherry blossom country, the most sold copies have games from the Pokemon series. The most prolific publisher is EA, followed by Actdivison in second place, with Namco rounding out the podium. Globally, the most copies of games were sold for consoles PS2, X260, PS3, respectively. Diverging from the global trend are the North American and Japanese markets. In the NA region, the Wii platform caught the podium, while in Japan the podium was as follows: DS, PS, PS2. When designing games, special attention should be paid to whether the product is to be targeted globally or to a market that differs significantly from the global one (Japan).
